05220nam a22008415i 9780520924444DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209244447 a10.1525/97805209244442doi  a(DE-B1597)543420  a(OCoLC)1153464056  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBL2525b.W85 1998eb 7aREL0170002bisacsh04a200/.973/090452211 aWuthnow, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAfter Heaven :bSpirituality in America Since the 1950s /cRobert Wuthnow.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (286 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tCHAPTER ONE. From Dwelling to Seeking -- tCHAPTER TWO. In the House of the Lord -- tCHAPTER THREE. The New Spiritual Freedom -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Desire for Discipline -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Angel Awakenings -- tCHAPTER SIX. Spirituality of the Inner Self -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. The Practice of Spirituality -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe evolution of American spirituality over the past fifty years is the subject of Robert Wuthnow's engrossing new book. Wuthnow uses in-depth interviews and a broad range of resource materials to show how Americans, from teenagers to senior citizens, define their spiritual journeys. His findings are a telling reflection of the changes in beliefs and lifestyles that have occurred throughout the United States in recent decades.Wuthnow reconstructs the social and cultural reasons for an emphasis on a spirituality of dwelling (houses of worship, denominations, neighborhoods) during the 1950s. Then in the 1960s a spirituality of seeking began to emerge, leading individuals to go beyond established religious institutions. In subsequent chapters Wuthnow examines attempts to reassert spiritual discipline, encounters with the sacred (such as angels and near-death experiences), and the development of the "inner self." His final chapter discusses a spirituality of practice, an alternative for people who are uncomfortable within a single religious community and who want more than a spirituality of endless seeking.The diversity of contemporary American spirituality comes through in the voices of the interviewees. Christians, Jews, Buddhists, Muslims, Hindus, and Native Americans are included, as are followers of occult practices, New Age religions, and other eclectic groups. Wuthnow also notes how politicized spirituality, evangelical movements, and resources such as Twelve-Step programs and mental health therapy influence definitions of religious life today.Wuthnow's landmark book, The Restructuring of American Religion (1988), documented the changes in institutional religion in the United States; now After Heaven explains the changes in personal spirituality that have come to shape our religious life. Moreover, it is a compelling and insightful guide to understanding American culture at century's end.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSpiritual lifexHistoryy20th century. 0aSpiritualityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aamerican culture.  aamerican religion.  aanthropology.  abible.  achristianity.  achurch history.  acomparative religion.  aevangelical.  agrace.  amaterialism.  amodern church.  anonfiction.  apersonal spirituality.  areligion in america.  areligion.  areligious practice.  areligious.  asecularism.  aspiritual life.  aspiritual trends.  aspirituality.  atheology.  aunited states.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Califo